\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(b) Gesucht: Alle Geraden 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\left\{ (x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})^{t}+\lambda(v_{1},v_{2},v_{3})^{t}\,|\,\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\right\} \subset\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 mit 
\begin_inset Formula $L\subset F$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(1) Es gelte o.B.d.A.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=0,v_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) Annahme: 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{3}=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

Gerade bewegt sich in der x-y-Ebene.
 Aber da 
\begin_inset Formula $L\subset F$
\end_inset

 so muss 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 dann ein Kreis sein.
 Widerspruch zur Voraussetzung, dass 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 eine Gerade ist.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow v_{3}\neq0$
\end_inset

 Nun können wir ohne Einschränkung 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{3}$
\end_inset

 normieren, sodass 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) Bei einer Gerade dürfen wir den Stützpunkt verändern, solange der in
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 liegt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also wähle 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=-x_{3}\Rightarrow L'=\left\{ (x_{1},x_{2},0)^{t}+\lambda(v_{1},v_{2},1)^{t}\,|\,\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\right\} =L$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(2) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L\subset F\Leftrightarrow\forall\lambda\in\mathbb{R}:\,\left(x_{1}+\lambda v_{1}\right)^{2}+\left(x_{2}+\lambda v_{2}\right)^{2}-\lambda^{2}-1=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\stackrel{}{\Leftrightarrow}\forall\lambda\in\mathbb{R}:\, x_{1}^{2}+2\lambda x_{1}v_{1}+\lambda^{2}v_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+2\lambda x_{2}v_{2}+\lambda^{2}v_{2}^{2}-\lambda^{2}-1=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\stackrel{(x_{1},x_{2},0)\in F}{\Leftrightarrow}\forall\lambda\in\mathbb{R}:\,\lambda^{2}\left(v_{1}^{2}+v_{2}^{2}-1\right)+2\lambda\left(x_{1}v_{1}+x_{2}v_{2}\right)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\stackrel{*}{\Leftrightarrow}\begin{cases}
v_{1}^{2}+v_{2}^{2}=1\\
x_{1}v_{1}+x_{2}v_{2}=0
\end{cases}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(*) Durch Koeffizientenvergleich
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fall 1: 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=0\Rightarrow x_{2}=\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $II:\, x_{2}v_{2}=0\stackrel{(x_{1},x_{2},0)\in F}{\Leftrightarrow}v_{2}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow I:\; v_{1}^{2}=1\Leftrightarrow v_{1}=\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fall 2: 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=0\Rightarrow x_{1}=\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $II:\, x_{1}v_{1}=0\stackrel{(x_{1},x_{2},0)\in F}{\Leftrightarrow}v_{1}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow I:\; v_{2}^{2}=1\Rightarrow v_{2}=\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fall 3: 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\neq0\Rightarrow x_{2}\neq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow I:\;\frac{x_{2}^{2}v_{2}^{2}}{x_{1}^{2}}+v_{2}^{2}=1\Leftrightarrow x_{2}^{2}v_{2}^{2}+x_{1}^{2}v_{2}^{2}=x_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Leftrightarrow v_{2}^{2}\left(x_{2}^{2}+x_{1}^{2}\right)=x_{1}^{2}\Leftrightarrow v_{2}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{x_{1}^{2}}{x_{2}^{2}+x_{1}^{2}}}\stackrel{(x_{1},x_{2},0)\in F}{=}\pm x_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow II:\; v_{1}=\frac{x_{2}\pm x_{1}}{x_{1}}=\mp x_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\mathbb{L}=\left\{ (x_{1},x_{2},0)+\lambda(x_{2},-x_{1},1)\,|\;\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\right\} \cup\left\{ (x_{1},x_{2},0)+\lambda(-x_{2},x_{1},1)\,|\;\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 mit 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Also gibt es zu jedem Punkt in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 genau zwei Geraden, die Teilmenge von 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 sind.
\end_layout

